  m_Name: anglerfish
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: Assembly-CSharp::FishData
  <fishName>k__BackingField: Anglerfish
  <fishFact>k__BackingField: "The deep-sea anglerfish lives in total darkness and
    hunts with a bioluminescent lure dangling from its head like a built-in fishing
    rod, drawing in curious prey before snapping them up with its enormous jaws.
    The male anglerfish is dramatically smaller than the female \u2014 and when he
    finds a mate, he bites into her side and physically fuses with her body, sharing
    her bloodstream for the rest of his life. Squid \u2014 Squid are jet-propelled,
    color-changing, ink-squirting masters of the open ocean. They have three hearts,
    blue blood, and eyes remarkably similar to human eyes despite evolving completely
    separately. They're also among the most intelligent invertebrates alive, capable
    of problem-solving and rapid learning. In a pinch, they can sacrifice a tentacle
    to a predator and simply grow it back. Giant Squid \u2014 For centuries, giant
    squid were the stuff of pure legend \u2014 no living specimen had ever been photographed
    until 2004. They can grow over 12 meters long, with eyes the size of dinner plates
    (the largest of any living animal) to gather light in the pitch-black deep ocean.
    Their main predator is the sperm whale, and the two regularly do battle in the
    deep \u2014 sperm whales are often found with giant sucker-shaped scars to prove
    it. Black Sea Urchin \u2014 Sea urchins are essentially a mouth on the ocean
    floor \u2014 their entire underside is a jaw-like structure called Aristotle's
    lantern, capable of scraping algae straight off rock. Those long, black spines
    aren't just defensive; they also help the urchin move and wedge itself into crevices.
    In healthy reefs, urchins are vital grazers \u2014 but when their numbers explode,
    they can turn a coral reef into a barren rock field. Ray \u2014 Rays are essentially
    flattened sharks that took up life on the seafloor. They glide through the water
    by rippling their wide, wing-like fins in a motion that looks almost like slow-motion
    flying. Most species are completely harmless, filter-feeding or hunting mollusks
    buried in sand, which they crush with flat, plate-like teeth. Some rays can also
    generate electricity \u2014 using it to sense their environment and stun prey.
    Snakefish (Snakehead / Oarfish) \u2014 (Let me know which you mean \u2014 here's
    both!)  Snakehead Fish \u2014 Snakeheads are freshwater predators so tough they
    can breathe air and survive out of water for several days, crossing land between
    rivers if they have to. They're powerful ambush hunters with a mouthful of sharp
    teeth, and in regions where they've been introduced outside their native range,
    they've become one of the most disruptive invasive species known to science.
    Oarfish \u2014 The oarfish is the longest bony fish alive, reaching up to 11
    meters, with a shimmering silver body, a red spiky crest running the length of
    its back, and almost no tail to speak of. They live in deep water and are almost
    never seen alive \u2014 which is exactly why, for centuries, these rare creatures
    washing ashore were likely the origin of sea serpent legends.   A couple of extra
    notes for the game design side:  Mosasaurus and Plesiosaur as bosses is a great
    idea \u2014 framing them as ancient, legendary creatures the player encounters
    in special zones (deep sea, volcanic vents, ancient ruins) would fit perfectly
    with the discovery mechanic. You might consider grouping Ammonite, Trilobite,
    Mosasaurus, and Plesiosaur into a special \"Ancient Oceans\" unlock category
    \u2014 a nice reward for players who've already discovered most modern species. "
  <fishImage>k__BackingField: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 7a852a48ca4e64eb78db56c327565f7c, type: 3}
